  "remote_port": 443,
  "prompt": "What is Inspect Element? How do you read the codes?",
  "response": "### What is Inspect Element?\n**Inspect Element** is a built-in feature in most modern web browsers (like Chrome, Firefox, Edge, and Safari) that allows you to view and edit the underlying HTML, CSS, and JavaScript code of a webpage. It\u2019s primarily used for debugging, testing, and learning how a website is structured.\n\n### How to Access Inspect Element\n1. **Right-click** on any element on a webpage and select **\"Inspect\"** or **\"Inspect Element\"**.\n2. Alternatively, use the keyboard shortcut:\n   - **Windows/Linux**: `Ctrl + Shift + I` or `F12`\n   - **Mac**: `Cmd + Option + I`\n\n### Reading the Codes in Inspect Element\nWhen you open Inspect Element, you\u2019ll see a panel with several tabs (e.g., Elements, Console, Sources, etc.). Here\u2019s a breakdown of how to read and interpret the code:\n\n#### 1. **Elements Tab**\n   - **HTML Structure**: Displays the DOM (Document Object Model) of the webpage. You can see the hierarchy of HTML elements (e.g., `<div>`, `<p>`, `<a>`).\n   - **Styles Panel**: Shows the CSS styles applied to the selected element. You can see inline styles, styles from external stylesheets, and inherited styles.\n   - **Interactivity**: Click on any element in the HTML tree to highlight it on the webpage and view its styles.\n\n#### 2. **Console Tab**\n   - Displays JavaScript logs, errors, and warnings. You can also run JavaScript commands directly in the console for testing.\n\n#### 3. **Sources Tab**\n   - Shows all the files loaded by the webpage, including HTML, CSS, JavaScript, and images. You can debug JavaScript by setting breakpoints.\n\n#### 4. **Network Tab**\n   - Tracks all network requests made by the webpage (e.g., loading images, scripts, or APIs). Useful for analyzing performance or debugging API calls.\n\n#### 5. **Application Tab**\n   - Displays information about cookies, local storage, session storage, and other web application data.\n\n### Tips for Using Inspect Element\n- **Editing**: You can temporarily edit the HTML or CSS in the Inspector panel to see how changes would look on the page. These changes are not saved and will be lost when you refresh the page.\n- **Mobile View**: Use the **Responsive Design Mode** (or similar feature) to simulate how the webpage looks on different devices.\n- **Debugging**: Use the **Breakpoints** in the Sources tab to pause JavaScript execution and inspect variables.\n\n### Why Use Inspect Element?\n- **Debugging**: Identify and fix issues in your code.\n- **Learning**: Understand how websites are built by examining the code of other sites.\n- **Testing**: Experiment with design changes before implementing them.\n\n**Note**: While Inspect Element is a powerful tool, be cautious when using it on live websites. Changes made are temporary and won\u2019t affect the actual website, but improper use could disrupt your browsing experience.",
  "temperature": 1.0,
